</table></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/bscarab5467.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jobrog>Jobrog</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 7<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/13/03 2:24 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Open or hidden bidding during loot auctions?</span><hr size=1> I vote for a hidden,second-price auction, also known as a Vickrey auction. It approximately gives the same result as an open auction. Economists has been researching auction theory since before most of us where born and the Vickrey auction is used alot because it gives the same results as an open bidding auction, but is much quicker. (Yes, I've been studying economics <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ).<br>
<br>
That is: Player A bids 5 Points<br>
           Player B bids 11 Points<br>
<br>
Result:<br>
           Player B wins and pays 5 Points<br>
<br>
There is no reason to add one point to what B pays (as was suggested somewhere in the thread), that is 5+1, since experiments has showed that players in Vickery auctions generally adjust there bids upwards.<br>
This could be modified if you by some reason want a minimum points to pay. Otherwise player B would pay 0 if he is the only one to bid, which in utility terms is totally ok. Why should he pay anything if he's the only one interested in an item? It's all about supply and demand <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
 <br>
